        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2986731653" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16784307375562645467">Although the story is fascinating, Kessel ruins it with his style which is simultaneously flat and overblown. A superfluity of adjectives is one of his lesser flaws. Also he is very uncritical of his subject who is presented as a totally bland kind of saint. Surely a man who managed to negotiate for hundreds of lives with someone like Heinrich Himmler had a lot more guile than the Kersten depicted here. By today&apos;s standards this wouldn&apos;t be considered journalism, nor does it succeed as a novel. </span>
  <span id="freeText16784307375562645467" style="display:none">Although the story is fascinating, Kessel ruins it with his style which is simultaneously flat and overblown. A superfluity of adjectives is one of his lesser flaws. Also he is very uncritical of his subject who is presented as a totally bland kind of saint. Surely a man who managed to negotiate for hundreds of lives with someone like Heinrich Himmler had a lot more guile than the Kersten depicted here. By today's standards this wouldn't be considered journalism, nor does it succeed as a novel. </span>
